{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"51433583-e856-49d9-b6eb-2b61d6d1fa8d","content":"`SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` was deprecated at the Android OS level (API 30+), which is why the MAUI wrapper stopped working. The modern replacement is **WindowInsets** via AndroidX.\n\n**In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:**\n\n```csharp\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\npublic class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity\n{\n    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n    {\n        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n        // Opt in to receiving IME (keyboard) insets\n        WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window!, false);\n\n        var content = Window!.DecorView.FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!;\n        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(content, new InsetsListener());\n    }\n\n    class InsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener\n    {\n        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(\n            Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)\n        {\n            var ime  = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());\n            var bars = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());\n\n            // Use whichever is taller: keyboard or nav bar\n            v.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, Math.Max(ime.Bottom, bars.Bottom));\n            return insets;\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**How it works:**\n- `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(false)` tells Android your app will handle insets itself (edge-to-edge mode).\n- The `InsetsListener` fires whenever the keyboard opens/closes, and adjusts the bottom padding of the content view so your input bar is pushed above the keyboard.\n\n**Layout tip** â€” structure your chat page so the input bar is naturally at the bottom:\n\n```xml\n<Grid RowDefinitions=\"*,Auto\">\n    <CollectionView Grid.Row=\"0\" ... />\n    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row=\"1\">\n        <Entry Placeholder=\"Message...\" HorizontalOptions=\"FillAndExpand\" />\n        <Button Text=\"Send\" />\n    </HorizontalStackLayout>\n</Grid>\n```\n\nRemove any old `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust` calls â€” they're no-ops now. This approach works on all Android API levels supported by .NET 10 MAUI.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e4eb7144-1a05-410d-acf0-18db95134a84","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI issue with keyboard handling in .NET 10. This is a known change â€” in .NET 9+, `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` was deprecated/removed because Android itself deprecated the `adjustResize` soft input mode. The replacement in .NET MAUI is to use the new `KeyboardAcceleratorsChanged` or more specifically, the `IEdgeToEdge` / `AndroidX` approach with `WindowInsetsCompat`.\n\nLet me think about what the correct answer is for .NET 10 MAUI:\n\n1. `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` was based on Android's `adjustResize` which was deprecated in Android 11 (API 30).\n\n\n2. In .NET MAUI, the recommended approach shifted starting around .NET 8/9, and for .NET 10 the solution involves using `WindowInsets` and edge-to-edge handling.\n3. The modern approach uses `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows` and `ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener` to handle insets properly, though the older `android:windowSoftInputMode=\"adjustResize\"` in AndroidManifest.xml still works for backward compatibility but is deprecated.\n\nFor .NET MAUI specifically, I can set the soft input mode directly in the MainActivity or through the platform configuration, though some of the older APIs like `UseWindowSoftInputModeAdjust` have been marked obsolete. The newer approach in .NET 8+ also introduced keyboard auto-scrolling features, but the core solution for handling the keyboard layout issue on Android involves configuring the soft input mode at the platform level.\n\nActually, I'm realizing that Android deprecated `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` in newer versions, so the `Resize` option doesn't work reliably anymore. The practical alternatives are using `adjustPan` in the manifest to shift the window when the keyboard appears, or handling the keyboard insets manually through the Android platform code to adjust padding dynamically. The edge-to-edge APIs with proper insets handling would be the most modern approach for .NET 10.\n\nFor a chat screen specifically, I should set up the MainActivity to listen for keyboard insets and adjust the layout padding accordingly...\n\nSetting up insets listener... Finishing the listener method...\n\nActually, let me reconsider the approach for .NET MAUI. The `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust` is outdated, and for .NET 8 and later, MAUI has built-in `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` that handles keyboard appearance automatically. If that's not working for a chat layout, the issue might be with how the layout is structured rather than needing custom inset handling. A typical chat screen should have a scrollable message list taking up the available space with an input field below it.\n\nFor a more direct solution, I can use the Android `WindowInsets` API in the `MainActivity` to detect when the keyboard appears and adjust the page's bottom padding accordingly. This involves enabling edge-to-edge rendering and setting up an inset listener...\n\nSetting up the inset listener... Finishing the padding setup and returning the insets, then using a Grid layout in XAML with the entry bar positioned at the bottom to handle the keyboard and navigation bar spacing properly.","outputTokens":2441,"requestId":"1108:33188C:194DA24:1C88BF6:69FE887B"},"id":"dfcb8cf3-e136-4da8-8525-e758ad9578d9","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:06:48.039Z","parentId":"d40d7260-a424-45ca-bb0c-2ebcd327d15f"}
